out Donor Anonymity Policies: A UK Perspective -- tPart Three: Commodification and Commercialization of Assisted Human Reproduction, Access and Funding of AHR, and the Role of Law -- t11. Assisted Reproductive Technology Use among Neighbours: Commercialization Concerns in Canada and the United States, in the Global Context -- t12. Fruitful Diversity: Revisiting the Enforceability of Gestational Carriage Contracts -- t13. Listening to LGBTQ People on Assisted Human Reproduction: Access to Reproductive Material, Services, and Facilities -- t14. Regulatory Failure: The Case of the Private-for-Profit IVF Sector -- t15. Great Expectations: Access to Assisted Reproductive Services and Reproductive Rights -- t16. The Commodification of Gametes: Why Prohibiting Untrammelled Commercialization Matters -- tAppendix: Expert Reports -- tAppendix 1: Quebec: A Pioneer in the Regulation of AHR and Research in Canada [Expert Opinion for the Government of Quebec] -- tAppendix 2: The Regulation of Assisted Human Reproductive Technologies and Related Research: A Public Health, Safety and Morality Argument [Expert Opinion for the Federal Government] -- tAppendix 3: Response to the Second Opinion of Françoise Baylis -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 2004, the Assisted Human Reproduction Act was passed by the Parliament of Canada. Fully in force by 2007, the act was intended to safeguard and promote the health, safety, dignity, and rights of Canadians. However, a 2010 Supreme Court of Canada decision ruled that key parts of the act were invalid. Regulating Creation is a collection of essays built around the 2010 ruling. Featuring contributions by Canadian and international scholars, it offers a variety of perspectives on the role of law in dealing with the legal, ethical, and policy issues surrounding changing reproductive technologies. In addition to the in-depth analysis of the Canadian case the volume reflects on how other countries, particularly the U.S., U.K. and New Zealand regulate these same issues. Combining a detailed discussion of legal approaches with an in-depth exploration of societal implications, Regulating Creation deftly navigates the obstacles of legal policy amidst the rapid current of reproductive technological innovation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aHuman reproductive technologyxGovernment policyzCanada. 0aHuman reproductive technologyxLaw and legislationzCanada. 0aHuman reproductive technologyxMoral and ethical aspectszCanada. 7aHEALTH & FITNESS / Health Care Issues.2bisacsh1 aBaylis, Françoise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDickens, Bernard M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDrummond, Susan G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEpstein, Rachel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlood, Colleen M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiroux, Michelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreen, Datejie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGruben, Vanessa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuichon, Juliet R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHudson, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIkemoto, Iisa C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnoppers, Bartha Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKong, Hoi L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLee, Ian B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relator